DESCRIPTION

	A [Bully] leader election algorithm implementation for [ESP32-C3] microcontrollers
	family written in [Rust]. This project shows distributed leader election
	across multiple [ESP32-C3]FN4 boards using the [Bully] protocol.

	With recommended minimum of 3 boards, each of them participates in the
	election process and uses a single LED indicator on GPIO port #4 to
	visually display its current state in the cluster:

		* Leader: steady on
		* Candidate: quick blink.
		* Follower: slow blink.
		* Isolated: steady off.

	Communication between nodes is handled via [ESP-NOW], a connectionless
	protocol that leverages the [ESP32-C3]'s built-in WiFi capabilities for
	fast, low-power peer-to-peer messaging without requiring a router or
	access point.

	This serves as both a practical example of implementing [Bully] on
	resource-constrained embedded systems and a visual demonstration of
	distributed leader election in action. Multiple boards can be networked
	together to form a cluster where leadership automatically transitions
	if the current leader fails.

ARCHITECTURE

	Initially, [Raft] algorithm was chosen, but [Bully] took over because
	[ESP32-C3]FN4 boards, when placed in close proximity, exhibit significant
	packet loss. The [Bully] algorithm amortizes this by using static leadership
	distribution based on unique node IDs (MAC addresses), where the highest ID
	always wins - no majority vote required.

	The number of nodes in the cluster is dynamic: boards can join or leave
	at any time without prior configuration. New peers are discovered
	automatically when their first [ESP-NOW] packet arrives, and a missing
	leader is detected by heartbeat timeout (2 seconds), triggering a new
	election.

	The node firmware (`SOURCE/node/`) runs on [Embassy] async runtime and
	is organized as a set of concurrent tasks:

		* Hermes: receives [ESP-NOW] packets, deserializes messages
		  and registers unknown peers on the fly.

		* Governor: drives the [Bully] state machine - tracks
		  timeouts, processes election/heartbeat/victory messages
		  and performs role transitions.

		* Prometheus: maps current role to LED blink pattern.

		* Publisher: broadcasts node state as JSON over UDP every
		  330 ms for external monitoring.

		* Connector: maintains WiFi connection for the UDP path.

		* Runner: runs the [Embassy] network stack.

	The wire protocol (`SOURCE/node/src/wire.rs`) defines three request
	types and their corresponding responses, serialized with [postcard]
	into compact binary frames (up to 250 bytes per [ESP-NOW] payload).
	Every message is broadcast to all peers simultaneously:

		* Heartbeat: sent by the leader every 500 ms. A receiver
		  with a higher ID responds with an Election veto and becomes
		  a candidate; a receiver with a lower ID accepts the sender
		  as leader and resets its timeout.

		* Election: announces candidacy. Any node with a higher ID
		  responds with a veto, forcing the candidate back to the
		  initialization phase.

		* Victory: sent once after a candidate survives its waiting
		  period (500 ms + random jitter up to 200 ms) without
		  receiving a veto. All lower-ID nodes become followers
		  of the new leader.

	The monitoring broker (`SOURCE/broker/`) is a host-side TUI application
	built with [ratatui]. It listens on UDP port 9999 for node broadcasts
	and displays a live table of all nodes, their roles and last-seen
	timestamps. Nodes silent for over 2 seconds are marked as dead.

